gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcSw0eXjM2JRSSFVWqDPEYGIYAnEgmpOScfzEZYm2d2nzMt4ra1z2C8DO3FOKS67EB70SoI";s:8:"filetype";s:3:"jpg";s:5:"width";i:852;s:6:"height";i:1760;s:6:"source";s:170:"https://chem.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Organic_Chemistry/Map%3A_Organic_Chemistry_(Wade)/03%3A_Structure_and_Stereochemistry_of_Alkanes/4.07%3A_Cyclohexane_Conformations";s:6:"domain";s:19:"chem.libretexts.org";}i:20;a:11:{s:7:"keyword";s:27:"chair conformation examples";s:4:"slug";s:27:"chair-conformation-examples";s:5:"title";s:36:"Practice Drawing Chair Conformations";s:3:"alt";s:24:"best way drawing blogger";s:3:"url";s:196:"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/proxy/3i22D18Wls0vXHc11TruG0R7SGcYRfZt7Tm818O9-HjUx8tpS-Paxno57BGP9pjL2xgylQgr3KdmFD4gbHQ0c6SHIUS_wT3sePl8_rPzpMqcyzuVoVvV8oK-JpLprvGZ0xm6CBsKIGLTlG0qBcmpboQ=s0-d";s:5:"thumb";s:90:"https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcT2Lv685BweAGcdLmn7H-BraUqBStclE_b6mg";s:8:"filetype";s:3:"jpg";s:5:"width";i:287;s:6:"height";i:680;s:6:"source";s:85:"https://materiamemoria.blogspot.com/2014/03/practice-drawing-chair-conformations.html";s:6:"domain";s:27:"materiamemoria.blogspot.com";}}s:9:"sentences";a:53:{i:0;s:39:"Chair Conformations Examples - YouTube.";i:1;s:37:"If playback doesnt begin shortly try.";i:2;s:117:"The chair conformation has alternating axial up axial down so once you have that single axial substituent move on to.";i:3;s:82:"Alternate your axial substituents up and down all the way around your cyclohexane.";i:4;s:43:"Every carbon on the chair conformation has.";i:5;s:66:"So for 1R-33-dichlorocyclohexanol the two chair conformations are.";i:6;s:143:"1 2 2 1 3 3 4 4 5 6 6 5 OH H Cl Cl OH Cl Cl H These conformations can then be used to evaluate the absolute or relative steric strain energies.";i:7;s:51:"In a chair conformation with a few exceptions only.";i:8;s:227:"AK Lectures - Chair Conformations Examples Ring Flip of Chair Conformations with Practice Problems - Chemistry Steps How to Draw Cyclohexane Chair Conformations and Ring Flips - YouTube Cyclohexane Chair Conformation Stability.";i:9;s:26:"Which One Is Lower Energy.";i:10;s:47:"Cyclohexane conformation - Wikipedia Ring-Flip.";i:11;s:33:"Comparing the Stability of Chair.";i:12;s:34:"Chair conformation you start with.";i:13;s:39:"Drawing the Chair Flipped Conformation.";i:14;s:84:"To draw the chair flip conformation you have to redraw the ring as its mirror image.";i:15;s:77:"This will represent the new conformation as it should look if the ring flips.";i:16;s:53:"Carbon 1 which was an up carbon is now a down carbon.";i:17;s:31:"Carbon 4 which was down is now.";i:18;s:96:"For example the energy difference of the axial and equatorial isopropyl cyclohexane is 92 kJmol.";i:19;s:80:"So choosing the more stable chair conformation is straightforward when there is.";i:20;s:212:"Figure 71 Chair conformation of cyclohexane shown as a a ball-and-stick modelb a space-Ô¨Ålling modeland c a skeletal structureIn parts a and bthe axial hydrogens are blueand in part cthey are shown in blue type.";i:21;s:65:"Draw the ring flip for each of the following chair conformations.";i:22;s:44:"Dont forget up stays up and down stays down.";i:23;s:33:"As taught in this Tutorial Video.";i:24;s:91:"Draw the lowest energy chair conformation for each of the following cyclohexane structures.";i:25;s:50:"Draw BOTH chairs and compare energy and stability.";i:26;s:40:"For each of the following do two things.";i:27;s:37:"Chair Conformation Example - YouTube.";i:28;s:25:"If playback doesnt begin.";i:29;s:199:"The chair conformation is considered to be the lowest energy conformation because it lacks this means that the chair conformation is the structure that is observable in most reactions of cyclohexane.";i:30;s:96:"For example the energy difference of the axial and equatorial isopropyl cyclohexane is 92 kjmol.";i:31;s:44:"Chair conformation of cyclohexane axial and.";i:32;s:426:"Lets get some practice drawing it chair confirmations one way to do it is to start by drawing two parallel lines that are offset from each others let me go ahead and show you what I mean so heres heres one line and then here is another line theyre parallel to each other but theyre offset a little bit next were going to draw two horizontal dotted lines so the top horizontal dotted line is going to be on level with that top.";i:33;s:50:"A The two chair conformations are of equal energy.";i:34;s:103:"B The higher energy chair conformation contains one axial methyl group and one equatorial methyl group.";i:35;s:102:"C The lower energy chair conformation contains one axial methyl group and one equatorial methyl group.";i:36;s:72:"D The higher energy chair conformation contains two axial methyl groups.";i:37;s:38:"The chair conformation of cyclohexane.";i:38;s:228:"Other conformations for cyclohexane do exist and they include the boat half-chair and twist-boat conformations but the most important conformation is the chair because this conformation is typically the most stable conformation.";i:39;s:19:"How to draw chairs.";i:40;s:129:"Now that we understand the positions of cyclohexane Im actually going to take like five minutes just to teach you how to draw it.";i:41;s:160:"I know that sounds kind of juvenile but once again there are so many people that struggle to draw this weird shape that its not even worth it not to go over it.";i:42;s:23:"We should just go over.";i:43;s:55:"Ive seen chair conformation defined in that way before.";i:44;s:47:"That is the specific structure for cyclohexane.";i:45;s:86:"However other cycloalkanes like cyclodecane for example also has a chair conformation.";i:46;s:114:"The chair reference is just referring to the repeating zig-zag shape across the longitudinal axis of the molecule.";i:47;s:24:"Calculating Flip Energy.";i:48;s:159:"First we have to introduce the concept of an A-value which is simply the energy difference between the equatorial most stable and axial least stable positions.";i:49;s:63:"Explaining how A-Values are related to cyclohexane flip energy.";i:50;s:63:"Explaining how A-Values are related to cyclohexane flip energy.";i:51;s:164:"In the chair conformation there are two planes with carbon atoms alternating making carbon atoms 1 3 and 5 in one plane and carbon atoms 2 4 and 6 in another plane.";i:52;s:370:"The vector stencils library Conformations contains 32 symbols of ring conformations Newman and Fisher projections for chemical and biochemical drawing the molecular models and structural formulas of organic molecules and biochemical metabolites the conformers spatial structures of organic molecules the schemes of stereospecific chemical reactions in organic synthesis.";}}